Transversus Abdominis will NOT pop up into your fingers!⁣
⁣
One thing I hear being taught in different places around the world is that TrAb can be palpated easily. I think I can sense the action of Transversus but it isn’t easy for someone who isn’t an experienced manual therapist. ⁣
⁣
But I see people telling me they can activate their Transversus and proceed to show me an internal oblique contraction!⁣
⁣
In this video, this 20yo with no diastasis or problems is doing a crunch. She does Pilates and yoga. So she has a lot of obliques being used, less rectus. All good! But check out how her Transversus automatically pulls hard - much harder than when she isolates it (a future video). ⁣
⁣
Just work on moving in different ways. ⁣
⁣
And stop worrying about trying to feel your Transversus - if you are isolating it, you probably aren’t moving anything else anyway…⁣
⁣
Tell me what you think and ask any questions in the comments below. Tag educators who think they can feel Transversus pop up! We have to get this right!

This is a TRUE story.

Sami is a mother of two children, a 3.5 year old and 1 year old.

Sami had a very quick birth with her second, and reports having Stage 3 rectocele/posterior wall prolapse as well as Stage 2 uterine and cystocele/anterior wall prolapse.

She had an epidural with both children and felt the births were a positive experience, other than the prolapses. 

Sami felt she was coached to push with her second even though he felt high in the birth canal and she felt things ‘mush’ at that time. 

She rested for 6-8 weeks after birth and didn’t feel symptoms then, but when she returned to working out she felt everything fall.

Sami had an x-ray which confirmed a 5mm gap at the pubic symphysis, which gets aggravated from time to time with asymmetrical jumping activities. 

Sami does have a ring pessary that she wears when she has symptoms.  It helps, but she still feels like she can’t do jumping activities because of the heaviness.

Sami reports she can control her bladder most of the time, but if she is at a trampoline park she needs to contract her pelvic floor the whole time, which can contribute to spasm feeling in the pelvic floor. 

In a 1 hour assessment, Sami is guided to change her symptoms with jumping.

It is not uncommon for me to hear stories from my patients and friends from around the world that they have 𝒏𝒐𝒕 𝒇𝒆𝒍𝒕 𝒉𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒅 by their health/fitness professional. 

I once told someone that walking was a waste of time. What I meant was that there are more efficient ways of exercising, but what I said actually served as a disincentive to them. They were keen to start walking regularly, and my words knocked the wind out of their sails. Instead of starting at regular walking, enjoying it, and maybe including more exercise, my words had the opposite effect and they didn't even start the regular walking at that time. 

Have you become feel fearful about your fitness goals because of something said to you by a health/fitness professional?

Do you feel disempowered or that you are not capable or even worse - not believed?

Do you feel like they think you are stupid and/or it was your fault?

I wonder if this is a common thing, or is just experienced in the circles I am in?

I try to do the opposite 𝐧𝐨𝐰, and I know 𝐥𝐨𝐭'𝐬 of health and fitness professionals also try. 

Sometimes our intentions are good, but things are said and we don't realise how it lands with the client (just like what I have done many a time!).

If you feel comfortable, please share if you have ever felt unheard or dismissed by your health/fitness professional. 

If you want to share what was said, I'd love to hear that too (but no names please). I'd like to shine a light on this topic and see if we can have some meaningful conversations about changing for the better.

Violaine became pregnant and had significant pelvic girdle pain in pregnancy. She continued exercising throughout her pregnancy on days when she wasn’t limited by the pain. She had a difficult birth with back labour and was unable to walk due to back pain for 3 days after her birth.

At 4 months postpartum she had another episode of back pain.

Violaine is now 7.5years post partum. She had gotten into Olympic Weightlifting the last 2 years, but had two back-to-back episodes of back pain. She had an MRI which showed an old pelvic stress fracture and tendinopathy in both her hips and she was advised to stop exercising for 6 months. She did that and is now back into Olympic weightlifting only, but can’t do heavy thrusters or other CrossFit movements without feeling pain behind her belly button, down into her pelvis and some right sided pelvic pain.

Myth Busting - Why do people think Transversus Abdominis pulls medially?⁣
⁣
I think this paper (Richardson et al 2002) popularised this notion which is built on research done by Snijders, Vleeming and others to do with “core” stability. ⁣
⁣
As far as I can tell, it is an assertion that Transversus produces a medial vector anterior to the axis of rotation. ⁣
⁣
I think the force produced by the ligaments are going to be similar based on the axis of rotation chose and therefore the force closure mechanism is plausible with this model. ⁣
⁣
But clinically, we see the TrAb pull laterally. ⁣
⁣
Happy to be wrong to be honest if someone can explain to me how it all works considering the TrAb pulls laterally or at worst, it maintains it’s position. ⁣
⁣
Thanks!⁣

Hard Doming vs Soft Doming in #diastasisrecti ⁣
⁣
People are fearful of making their diastasis worse. Fair enough. ⁣
⁣
But don’t be fearful because you see movement in the midline!⁣
⁣
The way tissue and fascia works is that if it is soft, it is extremely unlikely to stretch or tear. ⁣
⁣
Let’s keep it simple - if it feels softer than your abs, it’s probably fine!⁣
⁣
If the midline cannot be pushed in, even if you are pressing firmly, then back off a bit. ⁣
⁣

Do you hate marketing strategies about Diastasis that suck? ⁣
⁣
They promise results to people with #diastasisrecti using evidence that is for people with the smallest diastasis or not even a clinical definition of diastasis!⁣
⁣
Did you know that on average, up to 100% of pregnant people will have a diastasis by the time of their delivery? da Mota et al 2015⁣
⁣
67% will have no diastasis by 12 months postpartum. No special program. Spersted et al 2016. ⁣
⁣
Yes a lot will still have diastasis. These programs are for them, right? ⁣
⁣
Well, a recent systematic review by Benjamin et al 2023 of 16 trials showed in 6 of those trials they found an average of 0.4cm aka 1/8th of an inch decrease in diastasis. ⁣
⁣
Sure there are extremes but we don’t actually know why diastasis happens and we don’t know why 2/3rds of people, on average, seem to decrease their IRD (their “gap”). ⁣
⁣
I have ZERO problems with these claims…⁣

I’m trying to explain to you with the analogy of the house in the countryside, borrowed from @physiodetective, why it’s important to train.⁣
Even when we have some pain, symptoms, dysfunction, maybe related to postpartum (prolapse, pee leakage, diastasis).⁣
⁣
Imagine a house in the country, with a huge garden and a fence. The house represents our safe space, without symptoms, the things we can do easily, and the garden is the space within which we can move, our possibilities and physical capacities. The further we move away from the house, the closer we are to the fence, to our limits, symptoms.⁣
⁣
If we stay indoors all the time (we don’t move, we do few things, we don’t explore), the fence begins to get closer to the house, the garden becomes smaller and smaller until it even prevents us from leaving the house. Our asymptomatic action space is reduced!⁣
⁣
If, on the other hand, we often lean against the fence, in every corner of our garden, it gets bigger, the fence moves and becomes wider, it allows us to do more things, to broaden our horizons, to become stronger, to do more things in our asymptomatic garden. We will no longer be forced to be alone inside the house!!⁣
⁣
If, due to prolapse, or diastasis, I limit myself to making certain movements, I block myself from the fear of getting worse, I gradually reduce my abilities more & more and the symptoms will get worse even when doing nothing! And not just what I had, but my general health, my physical strength will deteriorate.⁣
⁣
If instead I use a progressive and conscious approach, staying on the threshold of my symptoms (as in rehabilitation) I will be able to make concrete changes to my physique & I will expand the spectrum of things I can do without having symptoms.⁣
⁣
That’s why I insist on pushing my limits in a studied and reasoned way! It gives me more and more air, more and more freedom, more and more happiness!⁣
⁣
Let’s not set ourselves absolute limits, let’s recognize our current capabilities, and do something to expand them.⁣
⁣

Tension and the Linea Alba: TL;DR - I think trying to find the right amount of tension, or the adequate amount to “heal” a #diastasisrecti is unnecessary and irrelevant. ⁣
⁣
Let me explain. ⁣
⁣
There was a focus on the “gap” - the Inter-rectus distance (IRD). ⁣
⁣
Then there was the focus on tension, not the gap. ⁣
⁣
But people don’t like “doming” which I define as being distension or protrusion of the abdominal wall outside the bony borders of the muscles when the muscles are activated, usually seen in supine-lying exercises. ⁣
⁣
But soft and hard doming is “tension” with soft doming being in the toe region to the elastic region of the stress strain curve and hard doming being in the elastic or plastic region of the curve. ⁣
⁣
I teach that you are likely fine if your are soft doming during your exercises. ⁣
⁣
There is no evidence that tensioning improves the width of the diastasis - in fact, all the evidence seems to suggest that you keep it the same or widen it despite your function improving. ⁣
⁣
There is no evidence that “trenching” of the depth of the midline (measured in “knuckles”) is relevant or accurate in the prediction of narrowing a diastasis or functional ability. ⁣
⁣
So why care about the tension apart from there being too much tension?⁣
⁣

When considering exercise & pelvic organ prolapse (POP), a common question comes up: what about those with levator ani avulsion (LAA)?⁣
⁣
A bit of background first...⁣
⁣
LAA occurs when levator ani pulls away from it's attachment at the pubic bone near the front of the pelvis. This can happen on one side or both & means that the right & left muscle shelves that support the pelvic organs now have a bigger gap between them.⁣
⁣
LAA is of concern because it's associated with risk of development/progression of POP.⁣
⁣
It can also make pessary fitting more challenging in some cases.⁣
⁣
How do we know if we have LAA?⁣
-Often we don't as it can be asymptomatic⁣
-We may have a larger genital hiatus on bear down & a gap may be felt where the levator normally attaches⁣
-May be found on imaging⁣
⁣
So, how do we navigate exercise in the presence of LAA?⁣
Should it be different than for those without LAA?⁣
Is increased apprehension warranted?⁣
⁣
Here are my thoughts:⁣
⁣
1) While genital hiatus will be larger with LAA vs before, it's possible for the remaining iliococcygeus & ischiococcygeus to hypertrophy over time to create a stronger though wider shelf (what exactly this means for future risk of POP we don't know)⁣
⁣
2) Risk factors don't sentence people to a certain fate, but they can help us consider what we can do to control the controllables⁣
⁣
3) What if reduced activity is its own risk factor - what happens to tissues when we don't adequately load them?⁣
What happens to our overall strength & the amount of IAP we generate for daily tasks as we weaken?⁣
⁣
4) We are so much more than our pelvis - activity restrictions meant to protect us from POP (not evidence based btw) may = sedentary lifestyle increasing our risk of THINGS THAT CAN KILL US (cardiovascular, bone health, etc)⁣
This must be considered too.⁣
⁣
5) Honoring autonomy matters. It isn't about what we want, it's about informing, guiding with strategies & enabling educated choices about their own bodies.⁣
⁣
I hope you'll join Antony, Terri & I on Jan 30 as we unpack the evidence & what to make of it. We'll have a live Q&A you don't want to miss!⁣

When I first became a pelvic physio, one of the most fascinating observations I made was the lack of correlation between prolapse symptoms & anatomical presentation.⁣
⁣
Client A came in with significant stage 3 prolapse but no symptom bother outside of noticing tissue bulging out when she wiped after toileting.⁣
⁣
Client B had significant, distressing symptoms, yet only mild stage 1 descent on exam (the amount found in 50% of 20yr olds who've never had a baby! Buschbaum et al 2006)⁣
⁣
And we see many with anatomical stage 2 who are symptom free, active & thriving.⁣
⁣
What gives?⁣
⁣
I'm not the only one observing this.⁣
⁣
Research has shown POOR correlation between POP symptoms & anatomical stage with “seeing or feeling a bulge” being the only symptom associated with POP severity. (Broekhuis et al 2009) ⁣
⁣
Clearly there's more to it than issues in the tissues 🤔⁣
⁣
It's well established that pain severity does not correlate with tissue harm in persistent pain.⁣
⁣
We accept that hurt does not equal harm - we can have pain without tissue damage.⁣
⁣
What if the same is true for prolapse?⁣
⁣
What if we also established that pelvic heaviness doesn't equal harm?⁣
⁣
It's completely understandable that when folks with symptomatic POP feel pelvic heaviness/pressure/bulging, they often assume it's their prolapse that they're feeling & more heaviness must mean that their prolapse is worse.⁣
⁣
And just like hurt *can* be due to harm, heaviness *can* be due to structural POP - it's just not always a reliable indicator. 🤷⁣
⁣
What if those symptoms are more driven by central sensitization than by true anatomical descent?⁣
⁣
Symptoms of pelvic heaviness may be influenced by pelvic floor muscle tension, fatigue, stress, anxiety, physical activity, laughing, coughing, yelling, hormonal factors, local tissue sensitivity (esp postpartum or postmenopausal), and so on.⁣
⁣
We can certainly feel worse without our prolapse structurally being worse.⁣
⁣
Additionally anatomical descent naturally varies as well based on a number of factors from time of day, level of physical activity, hormonal factors, constipation, etc.⁣
⁣
Spread the word & join the movement to change POP culture!
